It amazes me that with all this information and content out that people will still demonize a training tool. Some don’t like ecollars some don’t like flexi leashes some don’t like harnesses. The tool is irrelevant it’s all based on how you use it. To a grocery store clerk a skill saw for metal cutting may look like a torturous device and could probably be so in the wrong hands, but to the skilled construction worker it’s nothing but a tool he uses to build whatever jt is he’s building. Now for you to say this saw is dangerous and nobody should use it cuz you used it and cut your hand, is completely opinionated and not factual. When in reality YOU didn’t know how to use it therefore it didn’t go the way you planned. But if you were to say you know that tool looks to be too much for me and I don’t want to learn how to use it cuz it may cause harm then that’s a completely different and respectable statement. But don’t say tools don’t work or they do bad things to the dogs just cuz you saw someone who didn’t know how to use them. Just look at the dog they never lie. Zeus gets punished on the ecollar at least once a day cuz he makes mistakes and it’s important for dogs to be held accountable. And yet we’ve got a great relationship that nobody can deny. #dogtraining #adaptk9 #bullybreed

Most dogs are just over fed. It had very little to do with exercise. If you were to just feed your dog healthy food and the correct amount then your dog would be in good shape regardless of exercise. Majority of dogs are overweight and some of it is just cuz people don’t know any better and some is because they just don’t really care. They think “love” is giving the dog whatever they want when they want. When in fact that’s going to literally take years of their life. If you truly “love” them then do what’s best for them not what’s easiest or most comfortable. A lot of my clients will say their dog doesn’t have any food drive when the dog is actually just overweight and doesn’t care for food since they’re always in a surplus of calories. They’re are numerous weight charts for your specific dogs breed. If you’re still unsure then the vet should be able to tell you. (Don’t just fill the bowl up with random measurements, be accurate and read the bag) #dogtraining #adaptk9

I see this very consistently, especially with working breeds in clients. These types of dogs and most dogs in general need a consistent job. They need something to do every day that’s going to mentally and physically stimulate them. Leaving them in the backyard by themselves is not enough you need to exercise them you need to mentally stimulated them every day. Most dogs don’t get that and they get their 2 to 3 walks and then on their walk they react that has become their job that is how they get their menand the more you do that the more calm, the dog becomes people see Zeus in there like wow he’s so calm. Yes because I empty his gas tank every single day. Therefore, his gas tank is never full so he can just chill for a full day and we don’t do anything but if I take three days off of emptying that gas tank he is going to be nuts. This, along with teaching the dog the art of doing nothing, will get you where you want to be!  #dogtraining #bullybreed

(Full 2 minute video uploaded for subscribers) This is why your dog acts differently with different people in the house hold. They are constantly keeping score with whom and what they can get away with. They are opportunistic predators. If they think the opportunity is there they will continue to try for it. If I consistently stop there efforts then eventually the thought of that opportunity will start to die down since the dog is never successful. So if mom never lets the dog jump on her but dad does, the dog learns that with mom I shouldn’t jump but dad doesn’t care. This is the same with pulling on leash, not coming when called, not getting off the bed etc. if you don’t follow through the dog knows that and will know who follows through and who doesn’t. #dogtraining #malinois.

It’s not the ecollar that’s the problem, it’s the person who doesn’t know how to use it. Or it’s the cheap low quality ecollar. You should not be buying an ecollar that’s under $125. You should not use one if you don’t know how. And if you have never seen or taught a dog to respond to ecollar humanely then you shouldn’t be judge-mental on something you don’t even understand. I deal with seriously reactive dogs and the clarity and confidence the ecollar has brought to the handlers and dogs is amazing. This tool has literally helped keep dogs in homes and evidently saving their lives. Don’t judge something based off on bad experience you may have saw or had with your dog. And if you haven’t needed an ecollar for your dog that’s great, but i guarantee your dog isn’t like a lot of the dogs I train and it’s not till you get a dog like that where you may need this tool. Does every dog need one? No. But can every dog benefit from them? Yes. And if you want your dog off leash I always recommend ecollar training. If you don’t care for that then you may not need one! Don’t try to fix resource guarding prevented, keeping the dog separate not letting them still each other’s food or toys and me not messing with them while they’re busy eating their food or their bones. The most common way to get your dog to resource guard around you is to start taking their stuff just to make sure you can take it Zeus used to resource guard and he did it because I would constantly take his bones just to make sure that I could take it and eventually it did a lot of damage to our relationship that I’m still repairing show your dog you’re a value when you show up not a nuisance. Some dogs will genetically resource card no matter what you do. These dogs should be fed in the crate no children should be around there should not be any toys are bones on the floor and that will be a management lifestyle. If your dog only experiences stress around triggers, theyre quickly going to have a negative relationship around triggers even more so. If you want your dog to be able to handle the stress of triggers without reacting, they need to have moments where they successfully push through stressful situations that don’t involve the triggers. This could be as simple as staying on a placemat, waiting to be let outside the crate, staying in a loose leash walk, jumping on top of something they don’t believe they can but we know they can. These are ways we show our dogs how to handle stress and be successful, because waiting, for a dog is stressful not being confident enough to jump up on something is stressful, staying in the loose leash, walking, not running towards every sniff and dog in person around you can be stressful. It’s important our dog experiences stress away from triggers so they can learn how to deal with it. Then that will begin to bleed into the experiences when there are triggers around the dog now has a better threshold for stress, and can think more clearly. #dogtraining #husky #bullybreed

Most dog bites happen cuz dogs and kids are left unsupervised, or parents never taught the kids how to respectfully interact with dogs. Kids and dogs should never be left alone together no matter how much you trust the dog. Most dog bites could be prevented if parents showed the kids how to respect the dog or if the child is too young for that then the parent has to make sure they’re always separated. Dogs very rarely bite out of no where. Constant lip licking, side eye, dog moving away from the child, these are all signs that your dogs probably not comfortable with what’s going on. A lot of people will say “but they’ve never snapped at the kid” and I always reply with “yet”. Every dog has its boiling point and once the reach that point they communicate with their teeth. Be the advocate for your dog or they’ll advocate for themselves in ways that could be deadly. #dogtraining

Your dog can play with other dogs and still listen to you then that’s not an issue but if they ignore you then I would be hesitating to let them play. Or or or your dog has lived in a bubble without ever been taught how to go through stress and become successful through it. And letting your dog do whatever they want for some time then you go to set a boundary and they’re caught so off guard and don’t have the capacity to handle the stress of not doing what they want. Therefore they shut down. Equivalent to never telling your child no till they’re 8 years old and you say they can’t have something and they flip and flop on the floor screaming cuz they don’t know the concept of sometimes you don’t get to do what you want. And if that’s your case, setting those boundaries are even more important now. Stress is unavoidable. It’s our job to show our dog how to handle it and work through it. Not avoid it. #dogtraining
